Strong-field physics and attosecond science \cite{sclass,reiss,sclass2,Lew,sclass4} have been largely founded on the semi-classical approaches, treating the electron
quantum-mechanically and the electromagnetic field classically. This is because the high photon number limit pertinent
to experiments with intense laser pulses appears to be adequately accounted for by a classically-described electromagnetic wave, which is not affected by the interaction.

In this work we develop a quantized-field approach for an ionized electron interacting with light field. We obtain a closed-form solution of the time-dependent Schr\"odinger equation (TDSE), which contains complete information about the laser-electron quantum dynamics during the interaction, and use it to describe high harmonic generation (HHG). Differently than previous approaches \cite{Gao,gaoguo1q,gaoguo1q2,Gao3,Gao4,tikh1q}, we describe the harmonic emission as far-field dipole radiation by using an initially coherent laser state 
and the obtained closed-form electron-laser wavefunction. From this wavefunction we can also retrieve the semi-classical Volkov functions by averaging over the light states. This is of advantage, since the main results of semi-classical theory \cite{Lew} (like electron paths, ionization times, recombination times, etc.) can be utilized in our quantized-field approach. Going beyond the reach of the semi-classical approach, we find that the quantum-optical properties of the HHG process are imprinted in measurable photon statistics of the transmitted IR laser field.

The non-relativistic TDSE of an electron interacting with a single-mode quantized light field of frequency $\omega$ reads

