where $\psi_{l}^{S}=\int{\Psi'(p,q,t-t_{S})}\,\nabla_{p}\,{\psi}^{*}_{g}(p)\,dp$ and $\psi_{l}^{L}=\int{\Psi'(p,q,t-t_{L})}\,\nabla_{p}\,{\psi}^{*}_{g}(p)\,dp$ are IR-photon wave functions directly corresponding to S and L electron paths. The wavefunction ${\psi}_{g}(p)$ is a ground state of the electron in momentum representation, $t_{S}$ and $t_{L}$ are the ionization times of the short and long electron paths generating the $\Omega$-harmonic, and $\alpha_{S}$, $\alpha_{L}$ are $q$-independent parameters. 

A scheme which can describe the HHG process in the context of the present model is shown in Fig.1. Although the quantization of the harmonic field is not required for this work and thus was not considered in the previous formalism, harmonic photons are included in Fig. 1 for a complete understanding of the process. Fig.1a shows the electron states in case of integrating over $q$ and Fig.1b shows the field states in case of integrating over $p$. The horizontal black lines in Fig.1a and 1b are the initial states of the electron $|\psi_g\rangle$ and IR-laser field $|\psi_c\rangle$ with energy $IP<0$ and $W_{\rm light}(0)$, respectively. At $t>0$ the system is excited (small red arrows) in an infinite number of entangled laser-electron $\Psi'_{i}$ states (gray area), resulting in a reduction of the average laser energy (small downwards red arrows in Fig. 1b) and the enhancement of the average electron energy (small upwards red arrows in Fig. 1a). The $\Omega$-harmonic emission is taking place by constructive interference of $\psi_{V}$ states and recombination to the ground state (downwards red arrows in Fig.1a). In this case the final laser energy remains shifted by $\hbar\Omega$ compared to the initial energy $W_{\rm light}(0)$. When the $\psi_{V}$ states interfere destructively the probability of harmonic emission is reduced and the average laser energy returns to the initial value (black dashed arrows in Fig.1b). Among the infinite $\Psi'_{i}$ states, two are the dominant surviving the superposition, corresponding to the S and L electron paths, described by ${|\,{\psi_{V,\Omega}^{\rm S}}\,\rangle}$ and ${|\,{\psi_{V,\Omega}^{\rm L}}\,\rangle}$, respectively. Correlated to them are the IR-laser states ${|\,{\psi_{l,\Omega}^{\rm S}}\,\rangle}$ and ${|\,{\psi_{l,\Omega}^{\rm L}}\,\rangle}$, as well
as the $\Omega$-harmonic states ${|\,{\psi_{\Omega}^{\rm S}}\,\rangle}$ and ${|\,{\psi_{\Omega}^{\rm L}}\,\rangle}$, respectively. This is consistent with the interpretation of recent experimental data \cite{Kom}.
