It is thus evident that by measuring quantum optical properties of the IR-light we can access the full quantum dynamics of the HHG process. Such properties, in particular photon statistics to be discussed next, are not accessible by semi-classical models \cite{sclass,reiss,sclass2,Lew,sclass4}.

The probability to measure $n$ photons in the light field state $\Psi$ is $P_{n}=\left|K_{n}\right|^{2}$, where $K_{n}$ is a probability amplitude appearing in the expansion $\Psi=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}K_{n}\,{|\,{n}\,\rangle}$, in terms of photon-number (Fock) states. In $q$-representation the Fock states are written as ${|\,{n}\,\rangle}=\frac{\exp\left(-q^{2}/2\right)}{\pi^{1/4}2^{n/2}\sqrt{n!}}H_{n}(q)$, where $H_{n}(q)=2^{n}\exp[{-\frac{1}{4}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial{q}^{2}}}]\;q^{n}$ are Hermite polynomials. For coherent light states \cite{quant}, the photon statistics are described by the Poisson distribution $P_{n}=\frac{N_{0}^{n}}{n!}e^{-N_{0}}$, well-approximated by a Gaussian $P_{n}\approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi{}N_{0}}}\,\exp\big[{-\frac{(n-N_{0})^{2}}{2N_{0}}}\big]$ when $N_{0}\gg{1}$. 

Although the interference of an infinite number of paths, $\Psi_{i}'$, leads to two dominant paths, S and L, responsible for the harmonic emission, we will explain our proposed measurement of IR photon statistics in HHG, starting with a few model cases for a single atom interaction. (I) a single path contributes to the emission of a single harmonic, (II) two paths contribute to the emission of two harmonics, (III) two paths contribute to the emission of the same harmonic, and (IV) the realistic scenario of multiple paths contributing to multiple harmonics.  In this discussion we neglect vacuum dispersion effects, i.e. we take $\lambda=a=-1/2$.
\newline
(I) For a single path recombining at time $t^{(1)}$ with electron momentum $p^{(1)}$ and leading to the harmonic $\Omega^{(1)}$, the probability distribution is $P_{n}=\left|K_{n}^{(1)}\right|^{2}$, where $K_{n}^{(1)}\approx\,\tilde{C}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n!}}\bigg[\sqrt{N_{0}}e^{-i\theta}+\frac{A_{0}\,p^{(1)}}{2\omega\sqrt{N_{0}}}\left(1-e^{i\omega{t^{(1)}}}\right)\bigg]^{n}$ is determined through the expansion $\Psi'(p^{(1)},q,t^{(1)})=\sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}K_{n}^{(1)}\,{|\,{n}\,\rangle}$.\newline
(II) Two paths (S or L) with momentum $p^{(1)}$ and $p^{(2)}$ potentially contributing to the harmonics with frequencies $\Omega^{(1)}$ and $\Omega^{(2)}$. Now we coherently add $K_{n}^{(1)}$ and $K_{n}^{(2)}$, $P_{n}=\left|c_{1}K_{n}^{(1)}+c_{2}K_{n}^{(2)}\right|^{2}$, where $c_{1}$ and $c_{2}$ are $n$-independent complex numbers proportional to the $q$-independent part of the $\Psi'$. In the high photon number limit, where $c_{(1,2)}K_{n}^{(1,2)}\rightarrow{}A_{n}^{(1,2)}\,e^{i\Phi_{(1,2)}}$ ($A_{n}^{(1,2)}$ is real),

