and $\theta_{i}^{(1,2)}=\omega{}t_{i}^{(1,2)}$ is the phase of the laser field at the moment of the ionization.\newline
(III) Two paths (S and L) contribute to the emission of a single $\Omega$-harmonic. This is a special case of (II) having $p^{(1)}=p^{(2)}$, while $t^{(1)}\neq{}t^{(2)}$.\newline
(IV) When multiple paths contribute to the emission of multiple harmonics, it is $P_{n}\approx\left|\sum\limits_{\Omega}\sum\limits_{k}{A}_{n}^{(k,\Omega)}\,e^{i\Phi_{k,\Omega}}\right|^{2}$,
where $k={\rm S,L}$ denotes the path. 


The above relations can be expressed in terms of energy by using $p=\sqrt{2[\Omega+IP]}$, and $A_{0}=\sqrt{2U_{p}}$, where $U_{p}$ is ponderomotive potential, and $\left|{A}_{n}\right|^{2}\propto\exp\left[-\frac{(n-\bar{N})^{2}}{2\bar{N}}\right]$, where $\bar{N}=N_{0}-q$ is the average number of photons after the recollision, with $q=\Omega/\omega$ being the harmonic order.

In reality, $n_a^{(q)}$ atoms coherently emit harmonics of various orders $q$. In this case, the coherent laser-atoms interaction is imprinted in the photon number $\bar{N}$ of the IR field as $\bar{N}=N_{0}-n_a^{(q)}q$, reflecting the energy conservation. Since the signal of interest, $n_a^{(q)}q$, is superimposed on a large background ($\approx{}N_0$), we use a balanced interferometer \cite{q-int} to subtract the initial IR photon number $N_{0}$ from $\bar{N}$ and thus measure $\Delta{N}=N_0-\bar{N}=n_{a}^{(q)}q=C^{(q)}n_{\rm int}q$ ($n_{\rm int}$ is the number of atoms interacting with the laser field and $C^{(q)}$ is the conversion efficiency of a single-mode $q$-harmonic generation).
