\includegraphics[width=8.0cm]{figure2.eps}
\caption{\label{compression} (Color online) 
Dependence of $P_{n}$ on the laser intensity $I_l$ ($\propto{}N_{0}$) and on measured photon number $n$ for $q=11,\;13,\;15$. (a) $n_{a}^{(q)}=100$ (upper plot) and $10^{5}$ (lower plot), in case the S paths contribute to the emission of the harmonics. (b) $n_{a}^{(q)}=50$ (upper plot) in case that only the S paths, and $n_{a}^{(q)}=100$ (lower plot) in case that the S and L paths contribute to the emission of the harmonics. The dashed vertical lines depict the cut-off positions of the harmonics. The ionization and recombination times have been calculated by solving the semi-classical model \cite{Lew} for Xenon atom and $n_{a}^{(q)}$ were taken independent of $I_l$.} 
\end{figure}

In an HHG experiment, the harmonics are coherently generated by a gas-phase medium during the interaction of a Ti:S femtoseond (fs) laser pulse with $\sim{}10^{17}$ photons/pulse which corresponds to $N_{0}\sim{}10^{12}$ photons/mode for a laser system based on a $100$ MHz oscillator which delivers pulses of $\sim{}30$ fs duration. The efficiency of the process depends on the gas density in the interaction region. Taking into account that for gas densities $\sim{}10^{18}$ atoms/${\rm cm}^{3}$ the conversion efficiency is $\sim{}10^{-4}$ (for Ar, Kr, Xe in the 25-eV photon energy range) \cite{p1,p2}, it can be estimated that $\Delta{}N$ ranges from $\sim{}0$ (for zero gas density) up to $\sim{}10^{9}$ photons/mode (for gas density $\sim{}10^{18}$ atoms/${\rm cm}^{3}$). 

In Fig. 2a we show the dependence of the $P_{n}$ on $N_{0}$ and $n$ for $n_{a}^{(q)}=10^2$ (upper plot) and $n_{a}^{(q)}=10^5$ (lower plot). It is evident that we can apply IR photon statistics to high resolution spectroscopy in extreme ultraviolet (XUV) without specialized equipment ordinarily required in the XUV spectral range. Indeed, the harmonic spectrum can be obtained from the maxima of $P_n$ centered at $\Delta{}N=q\cdot{}n_{a}^{(q)}$. The spacing between the maxima $\delta(\Delta{N})=n_{a}^{(q)}\delta{q}$ with $\delta{q}$=2 for consecutive harmonics, and the width $w=\sqrt{2\Delta{}N}=\sqrt{2n_{a}^{(q)}q}$ depend on $C^{(q)}$ and $n_{\rm int}$. The resolving spectral power $P_{R}=\Delta{}N{}/w=\sqrt{\Delta{}N/2}=\lambda_{\Omega}/\delta\lambda_{\Omega}$ increases with $n_{\rm int}$ (lower plot of Fig. 2a) and for typical values of $\Delta{}N\sim{}10^{9}$ photons, $P_R$ can reach the values of $\sim{} 10^{4}-10^{5}$ in the spectral range of 25-eV, which competes with state-of-the-art XUV spectrometers.

When $\Delta{N}$ is reduced to a point where the probability distribution between the consecutive harmonics overlaps, an interference pattern associated with the relative phase between the consecutive harmonics appears in Fig. 2b. Additionally, as shown in the lower plot of Fig. 2b, when S and L paths contribute to the harmonic emission, $P_{n}$ is modulated 
by the intensity of the laser field. This modulation reflects the effect of the path interferences in the context of Fig. 1, i.e. the maxima (minima) of $P_{n}$ versus $N_{0}$ correspond to those IR-laser intensities $N_{0}$, for which $\Psi_{V}$ interfere destructively (constructively). These observations can be used for attosecond science and metrology, to be explored in detail elsewhere.  

Concluding, we have developed a quantized-field approach describing the interaction of the laser field, being initially in a coherent state, with a charged particle. The electron-light wavefunction resulting from the closed-form solution of TDSE describes the quantum-optical properties of HHG, which can be accessed by measuring the photon statistics of the laser field. Finally, this work establishes a connection of strong-field physics with quantum optics and can initiate new experiments where the strong-field-laser-matter interaction can be studied by measuring the quantum properties of the IR laser field.


